<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0820-B"><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>Unlike the Kursk sinking, the August mini-sub crisis ended with all seven crewmen surviving unhurt _ thanks to an underwater robotic vehicle sent from Britain.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>Russian ships first tried to tow the sub to shallower water where divers could reach it but were able to move it only about 80 meters (90 yards) in Beryozovaya Bay.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>Speaking at a news conference, Holloway also hailed the Russian navy for quickly providing precise information on position and condition of the mini-sub that was initially trapped on a fishing net and then was entangled around an underwater surveillance antenna.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="10"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>He was forced to retract the statement.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>&quot;Only when the situation got critical did the navy top brass appeal to foreign countries for help.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="38"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050812.0373"><line>The RIA-Novosti news agency quoted Masorin as saying Russia tried to deploy a remote-controlled underwater vehicle called a Venom at the accident site, &quot;but when they started to use it, they used it incorrectly _ it was spoiled by our people.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>To conserve electricity, lights were turned off and contact with the surface was kept to a minimum.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>Many naval ships have been repaired and others were launched and some of them were already commissioned,&quot; Putin said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>I danced,&quot; she told Channel One television.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line><line>Russia's cash-strapped navy apparently lacks rescue vehicles capable of operating at the depth where the sub was stranded.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>The Interfax news agency quoted a medical official in Kamchatka as saying that the crew only had three or four gulps of water a day.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>But when the C-17 arrived near the city of Petropavlovsk-Kamchatasky _ some 12 time zones away _ such a truck was not available and Russians only had a forklift _ a crude vehicle that was unable to unload the delicate Scorpio.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>The Foreign Ministry also issued a statement praising the joint actions of the Russian, British and U.S. militaries in the &quot;unique rescue operation.&quot;</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050906.0263"><line>It was established that outrageous violation of the instructions by senior officials of the Russian Pacific Fleet was the main cause of wrong 'swimming and diving rounds'&quot;, Ivanov told reporters, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>NTV television reported that the cost of the rescue for the Russians alone was estimated by navy headquarters at about $1.5 million.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="12"><scu uid="85" label="Russia's rescue costs" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>Russian officials said later that much more oxygen remained on the ship, which Holloway said was plausible.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>&quot;We understood we were trapped.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>He was then ushered into the van taking the men to the hospital and did not reply when asked his name.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>The small Russian submarine rescued Sunday had become trapped beneath the Pacific when an old fishing net disabled its propeller and tied the vessel to an undersea Russian surveillance device larger than a drive-in movie screen, according to American divers who helped save the boat's seven crew members.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="21,22,36"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050815.0213"><line>Masorin also said the navy would buy a US$3 million (euro2.5 million) Panther, which he described as a more modern device than the Scorpio.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="72" label="Russia may buy robotic rescue vessels" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>After we'd said we were stuck, we just lay down and waited.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>Russia's quick decision to seek foreign aid was in sharp contrast to the sinking of the Kursk nuclear submarine in August 2000, when authorities held off asking for outside assistance until hope was nearly exhausted; all 118 crew died.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="13,43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>The British vessel arrived first, and the American divers accompanied it to the rescue scene.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>Gennady Bolonin, a representative of the company that made the 43-foot AS-28 mini-submarine, said the men had simply tried to be patient.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>The jubilation came after three tense days that started Thursday when the 13.4-meter (44-foot) submarine got stranded in 180 meters ( 590 feet) of water about 15 kilometers (10 miles) off Kamchatka's east coast.</line><line>&quot;She moved and we lost her out of the camera...and it was then waiting on the surface waiting for her to arrive.</line><line>He was pale but told journalists he felt &quot;fine&quot; before climbing into a van with the others for the trip to the hospital.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>Later Monday, Putin called British Prime Minister Tony Blair to express his gratitude for the British contribution to the rescue, the Kremlin said in a statement.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>Holloway said he did not believe that Russians exposed any of their secrets, saying that the British rescue team could see little detail and that it handed over the tape filmed by the Scorpio's camera.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050815.0213"><line>The Venom vehicle was similar to the Scorpio submersible flown in by Britain to help free the mini-submarine, which was trapped with seven men aboard deep in the Pacific Ocean.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="19,33,48"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>Ivanov said a special commission already had been appointed to analyze actions by the Pacific Fleet and the Defense Ministry, and added that those involved would undergo a thorough debriefing.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>Russian authorities thanked the British and praised the international rescue effort that included the United States, having appealed for help in a significant gesture to its former Cold War enemies.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="78" label="Russia praised International rescue effort" weight="1"/><scu uid="79" label="Russia thanked Britain" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>The United States sent remote-controlled underwater vehicles for the rescue.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="13,18,21,6"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>They had an estimated six to 12 hours of air remaining when they finally surfaced.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>But he indicated that the admiral was bearing the blame for a series of tragedies in the Russian navy.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>We just had to wait for a decision.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>&quot;We put on (thermal) diving overalls, and when you are keeping very close together, you get warm,&quot; Bolonin said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>I cried from happiness.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>The men, trapped 600 feet under the Bering Sea, were rescued Sunday after a remote-controlled British &quot;Scorpio&quot; underwater craft cut through cables and fishing nets that had ensnared their mini-sub since Thursday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>Royal Navy Capt. Jonathan Holloway said British officials had warned Russians that a truck with an adjustable bed would be needed to get the vehicle off the C-17 cargo plane.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>The men had worn thermal suits to protect them against temperatures of about 5 C (40 F) and were told to lie flat and breathe as lightly as possible during the rescue effort, officials said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050812.0373"><line>On Tuesday, Pacific Fleet commander Adm. Viktor Fyodorov said Russia would buy two Scorpios, but Masorin's announcement indicated that the Panther would be bought in place of one Scorpio.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>As of Monday, he had made no public comment on the mini-sub drama.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>The American plane carried its own loader of the kind that was needed, and its crew lent it to the British team.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>But the Pacific Fleet commander, Adm. Viktor Fyodorov was quoted by Interfax on Monday as saying that despite boasting a powerful submarine fleet, the Russian navy did not have the proper resources to mount underwater rescue operations.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="5" sums="22,37,44,48,6"><scu uid="67" label="Russian authorities criticize Navy after the rescue" weight="2"/></annotation></line><line>The Scorpio, sent in response to Russia's urgent call for help, arrived Saturday and spent six hours the next day cutting away the fishing net cables that had snarled the Russian vessel and its propeller.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="19"/></line><line>The Kommersant daily reported that the news only leaked out after a submariner's wife made an anonymous call to a radio station in Kamchatka on Friday morning _ nearly 24 hours after the mini-sub radioed an emergency signal.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>Instead, after the British vessel's robotic arm had snipped most of the snarled netting, Russian commanders on a nearby ship ordered the submarine's crew to blow pressurized air through its ballast tanks.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>They also had been running short of water, the men said Monday in comments on Rossiya and NTV television.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>Sea rescue vehicles were among the first Soviet-built vessels to be scrapped amid the desperate funding shortages that followed the 1991 Soviet collapse, but the Kursk tragedy had prompted promises that rescue vehicles would be given priority.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>&quot;It was cold, cold, very cold.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line><line>The men had worn thermal suits to protect them against temperatures of about 4.4 degrees Celsius (40 degrees Fahrenheit) and were told to lie flat and breathe as lightly as possible during the rescue effort, officials said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050809.0099"><line>The Russian navy &quot;has advanced submarines but does not have efficient rescue vehicles,&quot; he said Monday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="13,20,22"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050815.0213"><line>The Scorpio provided by Britain succeeded in cutting through cables that had trapped the mini-sub near the ocean floor.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>&quot;We thought about it, and we said that we would need one,&quot; Holloway told The Associated Press.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>Uybin agreed.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>In telephone interviews, two of them said the Russian vessel floated to the surface from a depth of 625 feet off Russia's Kamchatka peninsula.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="37,6"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050809.0099"><line>The British Scorpio played a key role in the operation to free the submarine, Fyodorov said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>Seven sailors rescued from a mini-submarine hours before their air supply would have run out faced a new problem Monday: Confined to a hospital, they wanted out.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="23"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>&quot;I was happy.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>President Vladimir Putin on Sunday fired the head of Russia's Navy, Adm. Vladimir Kuroyedov, and called on the new commander to boost discipline in Russia's flagging fleet.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="25"><scu uid="74" label="Head of the Russian Navy was fired" weight="4"/><scu uid="75" label="On Sept. 4, head of Navy fired" weight="1"/><scu uid="77" label="Masorin charged with improving Navy" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>When the Kursk nuclear submarine sank in August 2000, Russian authorities held off asking for outside assistance until hope was nearly exhausted; all 118 crew members died.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="13,43"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050906.0263"><line>The AS-28 mini-submarine was ensnarled on the Pacific seabed off the Kamchatka Peninsula for nearly three days in early August and was eventually lifted to surface with all crew members alive in a rescue operation aided by a deep-diving British Scorpio rescue vehicle.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="18,43,49,8"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>But by Friday, some officials had shifted to saying that it was snagged on cables connected to an undersea antenna meant to detect foreign submarines lurking off a major Russian naval base nearby.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>One of the men called out, &quot;To eat.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>Rogozin said he wants to know why Russia has not acquired underwater vehicles similar to the ones provided by Britain and the United States and &quot;why fishing nets and cables litter the area of naval maneuvers.&quot;</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050809.0099"><line>Defense Minister Sergei Ivanov decided to buy two remote-controlled, deep-diving Scorpio underwater vehicles for the Russian navy, Pacific Fleet Commander Admiral Viktor Fyodorov told the Itar-Tass news agency Tuesday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="25,29,43,57"><scu uid="72" label="Russia may buy robotic rescue vessels" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>The president has been silent through the present crisis as well, although his spokesman Alexei Gromov said Putin was grateful to all those involved in the rescue operation.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050809.0099"><line>&quot;If we had had a rescue vehicle of this kind, we could have rescued the mini-submarine within a day,&quot; Fyodorov said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>&quot;We weren't out of water, we just didn't have enough of it,&quot; said crew member Alexander Uybin.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>&quot;We have seen the level of training of Navy pilots and sailors, which has grown.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050815.0213"><line>The Pacific Fleet's deputy military prosecutor, Roman Kolbanov, said the officer had damaged an underwater remote-controlled vehicle through lack of professionalism.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>Kuroyedov said at the time that the sinking could have been avoided easily and there had been several chances to save the crew.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050809.0099"><line>Russia was quick to ask for international help after the accident occurred.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>&quot;At the same time, there were difficult events, tragedies,&quot; Putin said during the meeting, which was attended by reporters.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>Deployment of the British underwater vehicle used in this week's rescue of a trapped Russian submarine was delayed for hours because Russia did not have the right equipment to unload it from a cargo plane, Britain's military attache said Thursday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="29,44"><scu uid="71" label="No equipment to unload British rescue vessel" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>Defense Minister Sergei B. Ivanov told reporters that Russia has robotic vehicles similar to the British Scorpio, but it would have taken longer to bring them to the scene.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>President Vladimir Putin was criticized then for reluctance to seek international help and for remaining on vacation as the disaster unfolded.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>Air Cmdr. Wilson Metcalfe, a British defense and air attache, said that Britain would not charge Russia any money for the operation.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>&quot;We would not be able to solve all these problems even with the state's economic potential growing if we do not strengthen discipline and order and solve tasks of social protection of seamen.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>&quot;The main thing is that the people are alive,&quot; Ivanov said at the news conference.</line><line>&quot;They are alive thanks to their personal stamina and bravery, as well as thanks to efforts of Russian and foreign rescuers who jointly carried out a unique operation.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>Western officials have said the Russian sailors were rescued about three to six hours before they would have run out of air.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>New criticism arose within hours of Sunday's rescue.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="21,32"/></line><line>The seventh was kept aboard a hospital ship for unspecified reasons.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050812.0373"><line>Russia's naval chief of staff said Friday that the navy will buy a remote-controlled underwater vehicle similar to the one flown in by Britain to help free a mini-submarine that was trapped with seven men aboard deep in the Pacific Ocean.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="8" sums="11,19,23,25,41,48,49,51"><scu uid="72" label="Russia may buy robotic rescue vessels" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>That was really the tensest moment,&quot; he said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>Kuroyedov had presided over the Navy as it has suffered tragedy _ including the 2000 Kursk submarine sinking that killed 118 crew members _ and embarrassment, including his statement last year that a Russian nuclear-powered missile cruiser was in such dire condition that it could explode at any moment.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="8"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>&quot;The submarine was caught very firm into the fishing nets and had driven into them so that they were very tight and they actually looked and behaved like steel wires, so it was very, very difficult to cut through with cutting implements,&quot; Riches told The Associated Press.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line><line>&quot;It was a difficult operation, but we enjoyed doing it,&quot; he said as he arrived ashore at Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky in the early hours of Monday local time &quot;The team are over the moon that we have got these guys out alive,&quot; he added, saying he was &quot;elated.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="38"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>The account by the divers helped to sort out contradictory reports by Russian officials during the three-day race to reach the submarine before the sailors, huddled in the cold and dark, ran out of air.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>The British Super Scorpio, sent in response to Russia's urgent call for help, arrived Saturday and spent six hours the next day cutting away the fishing net cables that had snarled the Russian vessel and its propeller.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="19"/></line><line>Russian authorities thanked the British and praised the international rescue effort that included the United States, but criticism quickly arose over why the nation's once-formidable navy needed outside help.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="6" sums="10,14,29,40,43,55"><scu uid="67" label="Russian authorities criticize Navy after the rescue" weight="2"/><scu uid="78" label="Russia praised International rescue effort" weight="1"/><scu uid="79" label="Russia thanked Britain" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>After breaking free, a few anxious minutes followed before the vessel floated up to the surface, and the seven men climbed out onto the deck.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>Six were taken to a hospital on the mainland for examination, waving to relatives as they went in.</line><line>&quot;We have seen in deeds, not in words, what the brotherhood of the sea means,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>The remote-controlled vehicle was flown at Russia's request from Britain to help free the AS-28 mini-submarine that was snared in cables 190 meters (600 feet) underwater off Russia's far eastern Kamchatka Peninsula.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050906.0263"><line>Masorin also said the navy is considering buying a Scorpio submersible rescue vehicle.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="5" sums="16,32,37,57,6"><scu uid="72" label="Russia may buy robotic rescue vessels" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>Putin named Adm. Vladimir Masorin to replace Kuroyedov.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050809.0099"><line>The crew was salvaged at the end of an around-the-clock rescue operation that was assisted by a British Scorpio underwater vehicle, which was submerged to cut the entanglements.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050812.0373"><line>Although the seven survived the four-day ordeal, the accident and Russia's appeal for outside help underlined the navy's insufficient equipment.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050809.0099"><line>The AS-28 mini-submarine, itself meant for rescue operations, got ensnarled Thursday night by fishing nets and an antenna of Russia's coastal monitoring system on the seabed off the Kamchatka Peninsula and was lifted to surface Sunday with all the crew members alive.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>Foreign partners had not made any requests for reimbursement, it said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>President Vladimir Putin was criticized at the time of the Kursk sinking for reluctance to seek international help and for remaining on vacation as the disaster unfolded.</line><line>Defense Minister Sergei Ivanov defended the navy's rescue capabilities, saying Russia has a robotic vehicle similar to the Scorpio deployed at the Northern Fleet.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="13,51"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050809.0099"><line>Britain and the United States airlifted Scorpio submersibles to join the rescue work.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>To conserve electricity, lights were turned off and contact with the surface was kept to a minimum.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050815.0213"><line>Russia's naval chief of staff Adm. Vladimir Masorin said Friday that the Russian rescue team tried to deploy the Venom at the accident site, &quot;but when they started to use it, they used it incorrectly _ it was spoiled by our people.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>Last month, a mini-sub with seven men aboard was trapped at the bottom of the Pacific Ocean.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>Some Russian media said that the rescue operation could have allowed British and U.S. rescue team a glimpse at the tightly protected naval surveillance system intended to track down foreign submarines.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="44"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050815.0213"><line>Russian prosecutors have opened a criminal case against a naval captain accused of negligence in the efforts to rescue a mini-submarine stranded off the country's Pacific coast earlier this month, officials said Monday.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>At the edge of the gangplank leading off the ship that brought the crew to shore, the submarine's commander Lt. Vyacheslav Milashevsky held a long and solemn salute, then a slight smile crossed his face.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>Putin did not give a specific reason for firing Kuroyedov.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>Temperatures in the craft reportedly were about 40 degrees Fahrenheit, and the men tried to share their body heat during the ordeal.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050906.0263"><line>&quot;A scrupulous investigation into the accident has been conducted within a month's time, as was promised.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="8"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>Not badly, but we could feel in our bodies that we weren't getting enough.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>Russian officials first didn't mention the antenna, but then released the information after their own attempts to snag hold of the submarine and drag it to shallower water failed.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>Four U.S. Navy divers were on a ship to help with the rescue.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>Dmitry Rogozin, head of the nationalist Rodina party in the lower house of parliament, said he would demand an assessment from the Military Prosecutor's Office of the navy's performance in the incident, the Interfax news agency reported.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050815.0213"><line>The Venom's breakdown meant that the rescue operation cost an additional 10 million rubles (US$353,000, euro285,000), the prosecutor said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="85" label="Russia's rescue costs" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>&quot;All's well that ends well,&quot; said Holloway, who helped coordinate between the British rescue team and Russian officials.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="37"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>The divers, from the Navy's Deep Submergence Unit in San Diego, flew to the site on Friday with tons of rescue gear, including two American submersibles.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>Putin ordered the defense minister to launch an investigation and Kommersant reported Monday, citing military sources, that navy chief Admiral Vladimir Kuroyedov faced dismissal after this latest embarrassment for the fleet.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="56" label="Putin ordered an investigation" weight="3"/><scu uid="57" label="Putin ordered the Defense Minister to investigate" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>Putin on Sunday presented orders for bravery to the seven mini-sub crewmen and state awards to eight foreigners _ five Britons, one Japanese and two Americans _ who assisted the rescue effort.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>&quot;We realized we were on the bottom and reported it,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>He told Masorin that he faced a difficult task, in spite of progress.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>Russian sailors rescued with British help after three days trapped in a mini-submarine deep in the Pacific revealed Monday how they struggled with rapidly decreasing water and oxygen supplies while waiting anxiously in the darkness and cold.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="29,42"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>Putin ordered the defense minister to launch an investigation.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>&quot;The team are over the moon that we have got these guys out alive,&quot; said Riches as he arrived ashore at Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky in the early hours of Monday.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>&quot;When it's an international rescue operation, the country offering the help pays,&quot; Metcalfe told a news conference.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>Another crew member in the van looked from side to side, gazing at the green trees and gray skies.</line><line>Some naval officials had said the submarine was participating in a combat training exercise when it got caught on an underwater antenna assembly that is part of a coastal monitoring system.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>Strolling in the sunshine outside a military clinic, dressed in blue hospital uniforms, the submariners offered the first glimpse of the conditions for the seven men inside the cramped 13.4-meter (44-foot) submarine, snagged by cables in 180 meters (590 feet) of water off Russia's remote Pacific coast.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>The device is thought to be a large hydrophone, which scans the depths for the sounds of submarines, and it seems to be a vestige of Cold War cat-and-mouse games beneath the sea.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>The official, who was not identified by name, said the submariners had written farewell letters to their families several hours after their vessel became stranded on Thursday, the report said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,55"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>The new crisis indicated that Putin's promises to improve the navy's equipment have had little effect.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>But Moscow newspapers still criticized the Russian navy for waiting more than a day before revealing the submarine accident, accusing it of failing to learn the lessons of the 2000 Kursk submarine disaster and not investing necessary funds in upgrading rescue capabilities.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>The crew member with reddish hair said he felt OK and was eager to be reunited with his wife and daughter.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>There was also a problem with oxygen, not critical but the body felt it was not enough,&quot; crew member Alexander Uibin said in footage broadcast on Rossiya television.</line><line>&quot;As with the Kursk, the navy command tried to cover up information about the accident, trying to deal with it themselves,&quot; the Gazeta daily wrote.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050906.0263"><line>Violations of operating procedures caused the Russian mini-submarine to be stranded on the Pacific seabed for three days last month, Defense Minister Sergei Ivanov said Tuesday citing results of a probe into the accident.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="6" sums="0,14,43,5,51,9"><scu uid="61" label="Operating errors contributed to accident" weight="4"/><scu uid="65" label="On Sept 6, the defense minister announced investigation results" weight="1"/><scu uid="66" label="Defense minister announced investigation results" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>Later that day, Russia asked Japan, Britain and the United States for help.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>That lightened the submarine, the divers said, and propelled it upward with enough force to break the last thick strands of nylon pinning it down.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>Russian crewmen walked ashore unsteadily, rescued from a three-day ordeal after their mini-submarine surfaced with all seven crew members safe after being trapped deep under the Pacific Ocean in the frigid darkness.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="14,21,23,33,40"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>&quot;The crew were almost complaining about being put in a general ward. `We're OK, we just want to go home,&quot;' a correspondent for Rossiya television reported in a newscast.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>Despite the delay, Holloway praised Russian officials for their assistance and cooperation, saying that the seven-man crew of the AS-28 mini-submarine was saved thanks to quick decision-making and well-coordinated efforts from everyone involved.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="32,33"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>The Navy had no means of rescuing them without emergency help from abroad.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>A reporter asked what they had most wanted when they reached a rescue ship.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line><line>&quot;We were short of oxygen, too.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>They arrived several hours later and were not used, but three American divers and a doctor accompanied the British vessel on its mission.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050812.0373"><line>Adm. Vladimir Masorin said the navy would buy a US$3 million (euro2.5 million) Panther, which he described as a more modern device than the Scorpio sent by Britain that succeeded in cutting through cables that had snagged the mini-sub.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="55,57"><scu uid="72" label="Russia may buy robotic rescue vessels" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>Defense Minister Sergei Ivanov, who supervised the rescue operation from a navy ship, clenched his fists and shook them in happiness when he saw the red-and-white-striped sub surfacing.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>The need for foreign help underlined the troubles of a Navy that once was formidable but has fallen prey to money shortages and, many critics say, poor leadership.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>It also thanked Japan, which it said also responded to the request for help.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>At a meeting at his suburban residence with the two admirals and Russian Defense Minister Sergei Ivanov, Putin told Kuroyedov that the Navy he inherited when he took command in 1997 was in poor shape and that it had showed signs of improvement.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>&quot;Air-lifting of our deep-water robots to Kamchatka would have taken much more time.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>Putin's order said the foreigners' awards were &quot;for the self-sacrifice and high professionalism show during the rescue of the Russian seamen.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>Dygalo declined comment when asked about how the sub was trapped, saying only that it had been &quot;engaged in planned maneuvers.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>He said disassembling it for transport to an airport and then flying it across the sprawling country would have taken longer than it took for the British vessel to arrive.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>&quot;Of course, we couldn't wait to get the confirmation, because speed was so important.&quot;</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050906.0263"><line>Newly appointed Navy Commander-in-Chief Vladimir Masorin said Monday investigators of the accident found the crew had made errors operating the craft.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>When they said that they've put everything into action, we lay flat and began to wait,&quot; said Gennady Volonin, a representative of the company that made the AS-28 mini-submarine who was on board with six submariners.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050809.0099"><line>Russia has decided to buy two deep-diving Scorpio rescue vehicles to boost its rescue capabilities following a submarine accident that trapped seven crewmembers for three days after the mini-submarine got entangled with fishing nets and an antenna on the Pacific seabed.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="6" sums="11,12,16,20,41,43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>&quot;All we could do was wait for whatever decisions were taken.</line><line>&quot;Our mini-subs even eclipse Scorpios in some specifications, but trail them in mobility,&quot; Ivanov said at a news conference in Vilyuchinsk, in the Kamchatka region.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>But in August 2003, nine members of a 10-man crew died when the submarine they were in sank in gale-force winds in the Barents Sea as it was being towed to a scrapyard.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>&quot;The main thing was the lack of water.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>&quot;But I would like to underline once again that with all these problems, all these tragedies, the main thing is that the Navy is undergoing a revival.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>Uybin said his first wish when the mini-sub surfaced was &quot;to take a breath of fresh air.&quot;</line><line>There has been criticism that the Russian navy initially tried to keep the accident secret, and reports that news of it leaked out, triggering foreign help, only when word was spread by relatives of the trapped men.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="19,43"><scu uid="68" label="Accident notification was delayed " weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>But Riches, the British commander, said the vessel had become tangled in fishing nets, as had been originally reported.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line><line>The relief over the successful rescue attempt was in sharp contrast to the sinking of the Kursk nuclear submarine in August 2000, when Russian authorities held off asking for outside assistance until hope was nearly exhausted; all 118 crew members died.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="13,43"/></line><line>He was sharply criticized for his slow response to the Kursk crisis and reluctance to accept foreign assistance.</line><line>Milashevsky's wife, Yelena, said earlier that she was overjoyed upon hearing about the rescue.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050815.0213"><line>The officer was not identified by name.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,55"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>The men aboard the AS-28 mini-submarine _ six sailors and a representative of the company that made the ship _ opened the hatch and climbed out without assistance, officials said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>The problem was solved when an American C-5 military cargo plane arrived at the airport with more rescue equipment two hours later.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050809.0099"><line>The decision to buy Scorpios came a day after Fyodorov underlined the need to have efficient rescue equipment in the wake of the submarine accident.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="16,20"><scu uid="72" label="Russia may buy robotic rescue vessels" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>Whether she's going to make it all the way up, we didn't know where she was after that.</line><line>I can't even describe it,&quot; one crew member with reddish hair said as the sailors walked ashore Sunday with dazed looks and bloodshot eyes after their submarine was cut loose from fishing net cables that had snagged it by a British remote-controlled rescue vehicle.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="38,8"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050809.0099"><line>The lobster-shaped Scorpios are equipped with black and white video cameras, two robotic arms that can each lift about 250 pounds and a cable cutter that can slice through 2.54 cm-thick steel cables.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050811.0610"><line>He said that Russian officials told him that only six hours of oxygen remained on the mini-sub at the moment it was rescued on Sunday afternoon, local time, after three days underwater.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050808.0085"><line>&quot;Yes, to eat!&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0700"><line>The seven men had only six hours of oxygen left when they finally reached the surface, said Commander Ian Riches, the British naval officer who directed the effort to use a remote-controlled Scorpio underwater vehicle to free the submarine from fishing nets.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>They appeared to be in &quot;satisfactory&quot; condition, naval spokesman Capt. Igor Dygalo said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050815.0213"><line>Although the seven survived the three-day ordeal, the accident and Russia's appeal for outside help underlined the navy's insufficient rescue capabilities.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050808.0044"><line>The circumstances surrounding the cause of the accident remained unclear.</line><line>Commander Ian Riches, the British Royal Navy officer who led the successful operation using the remote-controlled Super Scorpio, hailed the joint rescue mission with the Russian Pacific Fleet as a &quot;marvelous example&quot; of international cooperation.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="6" sums="10,3,35,36,40,8"/></line><line>Riches said the most nerve-racking point in the operation was when the Russian submarine broke free from the cables and disappeared from the camera's sight before surfacing about 4:26 p.m.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>Though the ascent was uncontrolled, it popped safely to the surface between two rescue ships &quot;out of pure luck,&quot; said one of the divers, Lt. Cmdr. Gerard Demers.</line><line>The divers, who spoke by telephone shortly after returning to San Diego Monday, said the submarine had been knotted so tightly against the listening device that a British submersible could not maneuver close enough to clip all the netting during the tense, five-hour operation to free the craft.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050904.0576"><line>He blamed lower-ranking officials for disregarding safety rules.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0273"><line>After the 44-foot-long vessel became trapped Thursday, Russian fleet commanders first said it was entwined in a fishing net.</line></document></collection>